    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "One of the most annoying thing in the React InstantSearch codebase is to conditionally support single and multi index states. I thought we were going to a different structure in InstantSearch.js that will make development easier: always have the index ID as key and remove all top-level states.\r\n\r\n```ts\r\ninterface IndexUiState {\r\n  query?: string;\r\n  // ...\r\n}\r\n\r\ninterface UiState {\r\n  [indexId: string]: IndexUiState;\r\n}\r\n```\r\n\r\nAn example would be:\r\n\r\n```ts\r\nconst state: UiState = {\r\n  movies: {\r\n    query: 'hammer',\r\n  },\r\n  songs: {\r\n    query: 'burning',\r\n  },\r\n};\r\n```\r\n\r\nThe role of state mapping would be to transform any single-index mapping to a `IndexUiState` to keep routing backward compatible.\r\n",
    "created_at": "2019-08-26T14:06:01Z",
